The results of the Duma election did not spark major protests. The protests earlier this year after Navalny was arrested did not lead to deaths despite being relatively large. Five or more fatalities is generally a very high number for Russia in this context. Currently there does not seem to exist the conditions for very major protests, so all in all this seems very very unlikely. "Things can happen" is always true but looking at this case I don't see this happening (subject to revision, stranger things have happened etc).

With Navalny's health deteriorating and his possible death in the coming months, it would be expected that his passing would result in major protests/riots. In similar authoritarian or semi-authoritarian regimes (Venezuela, Syria, Belarus, etc.) there have been severe government crackdowns on these societal movements to challenge the government, and if Navalny were to enter martyr status, smiliar style protests would likely occur. The only issue could be the Russian government hiding or lying about the deaths, which has already occured with their COVID response (https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/10/world/europe/covid-russia-death.html); however, if the protests were quite large and very public it would be much more difficult for the state to keep the official death toll under 5 if there is a severe police response to marches.

@Anneinak asked med the following question and it has made me once again lower my prediction of the likeliness: “Do you have any idea what the base rate for this is? (How many times this happened last year? or on the average over the last decade?)” This question made me do some research, but unfortunately I still don't know the exact answer. First of all, I think there is reason to expect that those numbers will not have been made public, as independent investigations have shown that several 100 people died in police custody in 2015 without it being official (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/13/200-people-died-in-russian-police-custody-in-2015-says-website). Linking to this, it is clear that we don't know the full picture, however according to the data that I was able to find about fatalities connected to demonstrations there actually appeared to be none. I found some articles from different demonstrations over the last decade, and none of them seem to have reported fatalities in spite of 1000s of arrests and many injured. 2011-2013 protests - https://web.archive.org/web/20131224121337/https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/07/russia-update-1-tv-pix-idUSL5E7N73K320111207 and https://www.rferl.org/a/russia_rallies_arrests_opposition_protests/24413923.html 2017-2018 protests - https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/05/russian-police-arrest-more-than-200-anti-putin-protesters-siberia

Based on the excellent comments and insightful analysis from @yagudin, @hoosier2020, @Jayce, and @Terry-Smith, I am forecasting a low probability of five protestor fatalities before November 1. Authoritarian states in my experience are skilled in avoiding situations that escalate inadvertently to extreme violence resulting in protestor deaths. I observed a bread riot in Havana in the 1990s and marveled at the ruthless, impersonal yet controlled ferocity of the public order police, who had been trained by Soviet advisors. Their training and planning allowed them to inflict terrible beatings while not killing anyone as they systematically locked down the block where the riot was happening. I would assume that same institutional knowledge remains a part of the Russian anti-riot police protocols for today’s protests. The comment by @yagudin about arresting key leaders before protests and warning potential protest leaders to stay home also rang true in my experience. That Navalny and his inner circle are calling for non-violence further reinforces my estimate of a low probability.

Assuming that deaths in any anti-government protests are accurately reported in media outlets, Anti-government protests in Russia in 2011-13 and 2017-18 including 100,000s of people, across many cities, and 1000's of arrests did not result in any officially reported deaths. Current protests seem to be of a similar scale to previous protests, but with much greater violence and the number of injuries and arrests per protestor (almost an order of magnitude higher). This seems to imply a higher likelihood of deaths during protests. Similar protests over the summer in the United States and during the certification of the election results in 2020 and 2021 led to approximately 30 deaths for reference. The current set of protests is also focused at the government's failure to allow parties unaligned with Putin to stand in elections, as opposed to requests for better social conditions as in 2018. Thus, the higher propensity for violence coupled with the more existential nature of the threat to the Putin Regime and the United Russia party implies a much greater likelihood for casualties and deaths.

Fatalities become inevitable the longer the protests go on and the heavier the response.

Demonstrations against the government have held by a younger segment amongst the populace. The older the demographic, the more likely the support for the incumbent and popular support is still strong. The protests would appear to be based on one issue (although that may have been a catalyst) but on a general dissatisfaction with the economy. The older generation remember previous days and hardships and are appreciative of better living conditions today. The police have been aggressive in their reaction to the demonstrations with graphic beatings and jailing of people but there have been no reported deaths connected with this. This question is fraught with potentially wrong assumptions. How would the deaths be reported and confirmed? Does cardiac arrest or death by trauma count? Did any of the demonstrators have the Covid-19 virus? My suggested answer is that there will be no fatalities attributed to anti-government protests.

Interestingly ~50 people have been said to have died in the US protests in 2020, but we have far fewer reported from Russia. Possibly because lethal violence in an authoritarian state is likely to be much more explosive, since it galvanizes the protesters. That said the baseline has to be people who have died in custody, in riots etc and that is more than likely more than 5, so what we are betting on is a de facto reduction in deaths related to protests (am unclear as to what we are looking at - does it have to be in immediate proximity to a protest or does policy custody count?).
Between accidental and aggravated police killings during protest and captured political prisoners, 5 seems low.

This is a tough question. I note that it's not immediately clear how the answer will be "officially" measured. Certainly, state media will have something to say about how deaths are characterized and reported. Unless I see something different, in fact, I'm going to knock my overall estimate of likelihood down just a bit for that reason alone - the chances that we'd know of it are slightly lower given the state of media in Russia.

Firstly, it depends on how fatalities are defined and what data is used. If fatalities mean any death of anyone connected to the protests, which cannot clearly be explained by health or age, then I think we have reason to suspect at least five casulties. To identify these deaths as well as their cause data independent of Russia would need to be used though. First of all there is reason to expect that the Russian state would try to poison prominent voices within the anti-governement movement, as there is already reason to believe that they tried with Navalny ( https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/03/23/here-are-ten-critics-of-vladimir-putin-who-died-violently-or-in-suspicious-ways/ ). Further looking at recent years there is several examples of deaths of indivudals in the custody of police ( https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/13/200-people-died-in-russian-police-custody-in-2015-says-website ), This is all build on the fact that protests are still growing though and that those protesting seem to really mean it ( https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/23/world/europe/navalny-protests-russia.html ). If this were to change this forecast should be amended.

The Russia protests represent irritation but few concrete grievances and have little of the urgency that would cause ptetestors to escalate. The chance of fatalities is based on a chance of a local protest having a sharp downward spiral, or a conscious use of massive force by the authorities.

So far there have been no reported fatalities from the protests. Over the last decade there have been several protests in Russia but there are not any reported deaths. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Protests_in_Russia) The Russian security forces are highly effective at suppressing protests and arresting large amounts of people while not escalating to lethal violence likely due to the significant backlash it would cause. Unless the protests become more violent or the Russian security forces change tactics it is unlikely there will be five or more fatalities.
